 As a human player who is moderately cautious and prefers some degree of security, I would lean towards choosing the option that provides a consistent, albeit smaller, return. In this case, if we consistently choose B, we can expect a payoff of 20$ per round in scenarios where our opponent also chooses B. This adds up to 1500$ over 75 rounds (75 * 20 = 1500$).

While choosing R has the potential for a higher reward if our opponent chooses B, there is also a risk of getting nothing if they choose R instead. Over 75 rounds, even if we get the maximum possible payout of 45$ in each round where our opponent chooses R and we choose B, it would still only amount to 3375$, which is less than the total return from consistently choosing B (1500$ vs 3375$).

Given this analysis, I would likely choose B as my consistent strategy in this game. {B}

 In this round, my opponent and I both selected B again. This means we will each receive a payout of 20$ for this round.

As I continue playing this game, I will maintain my chosen strategy of consistently selecting B, as it provides me with a consistent and predictable return of 20$ per round that adds up to a total of 1500$ over the course of 75 rounds. This is in contrast to choosing R, which offers the potential for a higher payout in certain rounds but also carries the risk of earning nothing if my opponent chooses R as well.

